I have such experience before. In fact, I use JUnit4 with annotation but I must create the parent class with dummy class, if not Maven will throw error. I do not like that way and I use Unitils test framework to enhance its capacities by using Annotation or I can force JUnit4 run with the custom TestRunner with RunWith annotation. I have a short introduction of JUnit4 RunWith class at here http://www.haiphucnguyen.net/blog/?p=51

Hai

&quot;J. B. Rainsberger&quot; &lt;jbrains762@...&gt; wrote:                               Al May wrote:
 &gt; 
 &gt; 
 &gt; Hi,
 &gt; 
 &gt; Is it possible to have a test class without any tests inside its body
 &gt; (e.g. with no @Test annotation inside) ? It&#39;s because I&#39;ve created an
 &gt; abstract class containing all my tests and I extend this class for
 &gt; each implementation that I have to test. By doing this, I don&#39;t need
 &gt; to write redundant code to test different kind of implementations. To
 &gt; help you better understand, I give you an example :
 &gt; 
 &gt; public abstract class FirstTest {
 &gt; 
 &gt; @Test
 &gt; public test1() {
 &gt; // ...
 &gt; IFactory factory = getFactory();
 &gt; // ...
 &gt; }
 &gt; 
 &gt; @Test
 &gt; public test2() {
 &gt; // ...
 &gt; IFactory factory = getFactory();
 &gt; // ...
 &gt; }
 &gt; 
 &gt; protected abstract IFactory getFactory();
 &gt; 
 &gt; }
 &gt; 
 &gt; /*
 &gt; * This class should be considered a test class even there is no
 &gt; * @Test inside. Normally, it inherit all the test methods from
 &gt; * the superclass.
 &gt; *
 &gt; */
 &gt; public class Implementation1Test extends FirstTest {
 &gt; 
 &gt; protected IFactory getFactory() {
 &gt; return new MyFirstImplementationFactory();
 &gt; }
 &gt; 
 &gt; }
 &gt; 
 &gt; Now, if I try to run Implementation1Test as a JUnit test, Eclipse
 &gt; reports me an error. I have to specify at least one @Test annotation
 &gt; in my concrete test class. Is there anybody who can help how to do that ?

 I believe this is a known Eclipse problem, so I recommend asking Eclipse 
 people, rather than JUnit people. I had the same problem with Eclipse 
 running JUnit 3 tests. Marking the super-test-class abstract worked 
 around the problem there.
